<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
  Stark QoL Pack: Autonomy Timing Override

  Reduces how frequently idle Sims re-evaluate autonomy requests.
  The vanilla game runs autonomy evaluation every idle tick, which scales as
  O(active_sims * active_objects * available_interactions) and causes the
  simulation to desync from the game clock on lots with 8+ Sims.

  This override extends the minimum interval between autonomy evaluations,
  reducing CPU load without noticeably changing Sim behavior.

  Conflicts with:
    - MCCC "Autonomy Scan Interval" setting (if changed from default)
    - Any mod overriding autonomy.autonomy_modes_data tuning

  Compatible with:
    - TurboDriver's Simulation Unclogger (different mechanism: kills stuck actions)
    - LittleMsSam's Simulation Timeline Fix
-->
<I s="autonomy_timing_override" n="StarkQoL_AutonomyTiming">

  <!--
    Autonomy re-evaluation minimum interval (in Sim minutes).
    Vanilla: 5  |  StarkQoL: 10

    Idle Sims wait at least this many Sim-minutes before running another
    full autonomy evaluation. Doubles the vanilla interval, halving the
    number of expensive O(n*m) evaluations without visible behavior change.

    Values below 5 increase lag. Values above 20 cause Sims to stand idle
    too long before picking a new activity.
  -->
  <T n="autonomy_reevaluation_interval_min">10</T>

  <!--
    Multitasking break interval (in Sim minutes).
    Vanilla: 15  |  StarkQoL: 30

    How often Sims interrupt their current activity to check if a higher-
    priority action is available. Doubling this reduces mid-task autonomy
    evaluations, which are the second-largest source of simulation lag.

    Values below 10 cause Sims to constantly start and stop activities.
    Values above 60 mean Sims rarely switch tasks autonomously.
  -->
  <T n="multitasking_break_interval_min">30</T>

  <!--
    Maximum simultaneous autonomy requests per tick.
    Vanilla: 8  |  StarkQoL: 4

    Caps the number of Sims that can run autonomy evaluation in a single
    simulation tick. Remaining Sims are deferred to the next tick. This
    prevents the single-tick CPU spike that causes the game clock to stutter.

    Values below 2 cause noticeably delayed reactions on large lots.
    Values above 8 provide no benefit (vanilla bottleneck).
  -->
  <T n="max_autonomy_requests_per_tick">4</T>

</I>
